metadata.name: Takashi's Death #366
metadata.description:
Akira by Katsuhiro Otomo.
A global landmark in the shaping of the Cyberpunk genre, and a watershed title for the medium.

I got my hands on the tankōbon(s) more than 20 years ago and those pages upon pages at the end of the third one depicting the destruction of Neo-Tokyo stayed with me ever since. Pages of stunning destruction, leaving me in awe.

This is my generative take on the subject. An attempt to evoke the power of that one panel in a cohesive collection.

Everything procedurally generated at runtime.
You can find more info on the composition here : https://ulucode.com/wp/takashis-death/

Export a PNG capture at various resolutions by pressing the number keys 1 to 9 (top row or numpad, and only in live mode, after pressing "open"). Resolutions ranges from 720 to 7680 pixels ( height ). I recommend starting with "4".

More features are available, but a decent GPU is recommended:
- Press "space" to toggle an animation on/off
- Press "u" to Unlock the camera. You can then :
. Mouse left : Rotate
. Mouse middle/wheel : Zoom
. Mouse right : Translate
. "r" : reset camera
. "a" : change antialiasing quality : 3 settings in rotation. Try this if your framerate is too low.

metadata.name: Field Conditions #23
metadata.description:
Manual architectural drafting is thrilling. 

The precise control of the drafting mayline, protractor, and technical pen contrasts with the spontaneous, willful hand drawn line.

These drawings feel simultaneously mechanical and free.

This project was inspired by Lebbeus Woods's "Conflict Space 3", but I found myself also referencing the work of Allan Jacobs, particularly his beautiful book "Great Streets", and Marion Mahony, a long-time drafter for Frank Lloyd Wright. 

Relative size of marks, overlapping, and relative density all enhance the illusion of depth without actually modeling a 3-D space. I like how this small set of line styles can evoke so many different kinds of imagery and scales: viral particles, confetti, accelerating to light speed, contrails, cities at night, a camp fire, snow falling...

metadata.name: sun peel stare #27
metadata.description:
have you seen the sky today? (how often do you look?)

will it find you fractured or aligned? (or will it not see you at all?)

what don’t we see when the light is in our eyes? (do we even want to?)

[ in “live view” you can press: ]
[ P : process more/pause ]
[ S or 1 : save 3000x3000 png ]
[ 2 :  save 6000x6000 png ]
[ 3 :  save 12000x12000 png ]

(after initial render, you can save at any point of processing.)

metadata.name: Terrain Series, Quilt #89
metadata.description:
The first release from my experiments with terrain generation. 

Method: A quadtree is created from N number of randomly generated points. For each rectangle in the tree, particle points are created based on poisson disc sampling. The movement of these particles along the terrain + noise field is drawn with my rake-stroke method. The color of the rake-stroke is based on the noise value at the origin along with some other variability.

The loading time of the piece will be longer for some variations.

metadata.name: tur1ng #264
metadata.description:
‘tur1ng’ consists of audible image architectures based on the principle of Turing machines. These systems are mathematical models of computation that manipulate symbols on a strip of tape according to a table of rules. The machine first writes a symbol in a cell on the tape, then either moves the tape one cell left or right, then, based on the observed symbol and the machine's own state in the table, either proceeds to another instruction or halts computation.

In ‘tur1ng’, rules are stored as colors and the original tape cells are constructed from a two dimensional array. The sound unfolds as the algorithm proceeds: monitoring these binary songs requires being attentive to changes in the state or behavior of the system over time so that appropriate interventions or other process-related activities may be carried out. Another feature of listening algorithms is that it often has to be done as a background or secondary task or, perhaps, in parallel with one or more other primary tasks.

Touch to listen.

metadata.name: Rearranged #36
metadata.description:
Rearranged is an invitation to engage in an exploration of aesthetics within the constraints of the generated token. 

Each piece has 4 layers. Each layer can be independently rotated by 90 degrees clockwise by clicking 1,2,3 or 4 on the keyboard. Some changes are subtle. Some are surprising. 

's' on the keyboard will scramble all of the rotations.
'r' will reset to the original artwork.

You are invited to: 
arrange a more aesthetically pleasing piece than the original;
scramble the artwork and use the number keys to return it to its original state;
work out which shapes have been erased from each layer.

And of course there is also a gorgeous gradient illusion made of solid-colour filled tessellating shapes. 

3 tessellations of varying sizes, 12 layouts with random elements, 14 palettes.

Made with p5.js.
